         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Septr 25 /81 ¶ My dear Baron ¶  ¶ The case which you have so kindly directed to be sent with  ¶ Andersonias ¶ , has arrived, ¶  but with the plants  ¶ stone dead ¶ , as was indeed to be expected. It i...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">81.09.25</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M3, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS embossed with crest of Royal Gardens Kew. MS annotation by M: 'Answ 22/11/81'; see M to J. Hooker, 22 November 1881.</p>
               </note>Septr 25 /81</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Baron</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The case which you have so kindly directed to be sent with <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Andersonia">Andersonia</name>s</hi>
               </seg>, has arrived,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to J. Hooker, 12 July 1881 (in this edition as 81-07-12a).</p>
               </note> but with the plants <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">stone dead</hi>
               </seg>, as was indeed to be expected. It is quite impossible to send such plants alive in a Ward's case — they are most impatient of moisture, &amp; indeed it is by moisture that they are killed in our Greenhouses. In old days, when the water was not "laid on" to the houses &amp; the young and old Gardeners had to walk a good way to fetch every pot of water, these "hard-wooded" things were well grown — &amp; then the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">soft-wooded</hi>
               </seg> ones were starved — now it is all the other way, the soft wooded flourish, &amp; the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">hard wooded</hi>
               </seg> are <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">watered</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">to death</hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>These plants, <name key="Epacrideae">Epacrideae</name>, — can only be introduced by seed, &amp; that is why I have so often asked for their seeds. Mangles &amp; Drummond introduced most of them — all by seeds in letters. As did Cunningham &amp; his predecessors.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No plants could be better than these when put into the case by Mr Webb<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">William Webb.</p>
               </note> &amp; the case itself is in perfect order — the soil is quite moist — &amp; the plants are perfectly well packed, but they are dependent for life on a free circulation of dryish air, — the steamy interior of a Ward's case, or of a damp pit, is fatal to <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Epacrideae">Epacrideae</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Helicia">Helicia</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> seed sent by post arrived quite dead, I am glad of it, for the Museum however.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Thanks for the note about the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Nipa</hi>
               </seg>.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to J. Hooker, 4 August 1881.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have written to Mr Webb asking for seeds of them &amp; other <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Epacrideae">Epacrideae</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> &amp; informing him of the total loss of every specimen. — they have evidently been dead for weeks &amp; I cannot doubt but that the first heat killed them by raising vapor in the case.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We are accumulating a huge collection of Brown's plants for you<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Duplicates from specimens collected by Robert Brown (1773-1858) received at Kew from the British Museum.</p>
               </note> —do not suppose that you are forgotten here, but you have no idea of the work we have to get through in the day.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See also M to J. Hooker, 22 November 1881.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever sincerely yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Jos. D. Hooker</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Andersonia">Andersonia</name>
            </p>
